    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute global P95 and P05 (use the full available time series for that group). Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-19 22:25:08 UTC through 2024-01-19 22:55:08 UTC and identify anomalies defined as: value > P95 OR value < P05 (report both high and low anomalies). For each group that has at least one anomaly in the incident window, return a compact table (limit top 20 groups sorted by descending number of anomaly points) with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p05, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, latest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Also return the total number of anomaly rows found across all groups and the list of distinct cmdb_id components that have anomalies (up to 20). Keep output compact (no raw full series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous step we calculated global thresholds (P95 and P05) per component-KPI across the full series and found 249 anomalous metric rows during the incident window across 15 components. Top anomalous groups each had 4 anomaly points, with earliest anomalies starting around 2024-01-19 22:28:00 UTC and latest around 22:52:00 UTC. Traces are not available, so we must rely on metric fault patterns and logs to localize root cause. The next necessary step is to convert those anomaly points into 'fault' candidates (consecutive anomalous sub-series), measure their duration and severity (how much they exceed/below thresholds), and rank them so we can identify the most likely root-cause component(s) to investigate with logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "On metric.csv, recompute global P95 and P05 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available time series. Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-19 22:25:08 through 2024-01-19 22:55:08 UTC. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) within the window, mark each row as: 'high' anomaly if value > global_P95, 'low' anomaly if value < global_P05, otherwise 'normal'. Group consecutive anomaly rows into fault sequences where consecutive means timestamps differ by exactly 60 seconds. For each fault sequence produce one row with these fields: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_type ('high' or 'low'), start_timestamp_utc, end_timestamp_utc, length_points, max_value_in_sequence, min_value_in_sequence, global_p95, global_p05, relative_breach (for 'high': (max_value - global_p95)/global_p95; for 'low': (global_p05 - min_value)/global_p05). Return the top 30 fault sequences sorted first by length_points (descending) then by relative_breach (descending). Also return the count of sequences with length_points >= 3 and list of distinct cmdb_id components among those longer sequences (up to 20). Keep output compact (no raw full time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We converted anomalies into fault sequences. Results show many short (length=2) anomalous sequences across many services, but no long consecutive faults (>=3 points) to single out a dominant faulty KPI or component. Traces are absent, so we must rely on logs to further localize cause and reason. The metric anomalies include high relative breaches for orders latency, front-end memory, shipping memory, queue-master memory/socket, etc., but these are spread across services. Next, we need compact log-level evidence: aggregated error counts per component during the incident window and actual error log messages to detect signs of socket errors, packet loss, or resource exhaustion.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv and error_logs.csv: \n1) From log.csv, filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-19 22:25:08 through 2024-01-19 22:55:08 UTC. For entries with log_name == 'log.error_count', aggregate per cmdb_id returning: cmdb_id, sum_error_count (sum of value), count_rows, earliest_timestamp_utc, latest_timestamp_utc. Sort by sum_error_count desc and show top 20 rows. Also return the list of cmdb_id with sum_error_count > 0.\n2) From error_logs.csv, filter to the same incident window. For each cmdb_id, return top error message texts and their counts (group by message and cmdb_id), limited to the top 50 message rows across all components sorted by count desc, and include earliest occurrence timestamp_utc for each message. If error_logs.csv has empty or missing messages, indicate that.\nReturn both compact tables (no full raw series)."
}

